As much as I love my wigs I value the integrity of natural hair as well. These products have not failed me:

Olaplex- I use number 3,4,5 of their products. It leaves my hair so silky and smooth. Hands down on e of thee best products for all hair types.

@canviiy has a great product line all organic based and it’s amazing! I use the shampoo and conditioner. My faves are the grease and the scalp bliss which I use on ALL my clients who love it as well. The grease is so lightweight and the only one I use. The scalp bliss is great for those who have dry and itchy scalp!

Silk Elements- I love the heat protectant spray. I use it for my wigs as well as my natural hair.

Wild Growth- I use this hair maybe once or twice a month. A little goes a long way and it helped with my hair growth when my edges started thinning due to postpartum hair loss. 

Revlon- YES! I am relaxed! I’ve used Revlon MILD relaxer my entire life and it has never failed me. I relax my hair 3-4 times a year! Relaxers are only bad if you don’t use it properly. Overlapping/over processing, using it too often, using relaxers that are too strong, leaving it on too long etc! When used the right way you can still have healthy relaxed hair contrary to popular belief!

I realize everyone wants the super natural extra plucked hairline but if longevity is the goal it’s best to keep the plucking to a minimum.

1. The more you pluck the more you expose the lace which over time becomes harder to cover and maintain. It may look good at first but a week or two in and now you have bald areas. 

2. It sheds much faster and requires the lace to be replaced quicker. The hairline is typically the first place that starts to shed, over plucking speeds up this process significantly. 

3. If you have quality lace the hairline typically comes with a natural density that requires very little to no plucking to give a natural look. 

How much to pluck is really a personal preference. While some prefer a fuller hairline others would rather a thinner hairline. There’s no right or wrong way this is just something to consider when plucking your closures and frontals. For long time wear keep the plucking to a minimum.

When it comes to wig pricing there are several factors that account for the price.

1. Hair and materials is large percentage of the total. Quality hair and lace can be costly. Materials and supplies (wig caps, hair color, hot tools, hair products, shipping, etc) are also factored in. These are items that are necessary to create a flawless wig. Many are under the impression that the cost is all profit when the stylist only keeps a portion of the total after expenses. 

2. Time and Labor! There’s a lot of time and effort put into creating. Construction, bleaching, plucking, customizing. Several hours can be put into creating one wig depending on the style. 

3. Expertise. Many stylist have years of experience and are masters of their craft.  Numerous spend money taking classes to offer the latest trending styles and techniques to enhance their skills. As you grow your prices will reflect your worth. 

4. Quality and Longevity. Custom wigs are tailored for you. Yes, you can find cheaper options, but, how long does it last? How full is the hair? What’s the quality? How does it fit? Anything custom will naturally come with a higher price tag. Not to mention it comes ready to wear and you can easily install yourself saving time and money from a long day at the salon. 😏 

There are still great stylist that are just starting out and offer lower rates as they are building a clientele. You can use hashtags like #affordablewigs to find amazing new wig makers.

The most common thing the beauty industry is lacking is professionalism. So many have the skills but fall short when it comes to customer service and that’s always the detriment of their business.

There are a few simple steps that can enhance your customer experience and prevent you from feeling overwhelmed and burnt out when servicing your clients.

1. Don’t overbook! As a stylist you should know how long each style is going to take. Book accordingly.

2. Operating hours. If you know you are a late starter or like to sleep in, start your day later. One of the benefits of this business is the ability to create your own schedule. Don’t open at 8am when you know you’re likely going to be late. When you fall to far behind on one appointment your entire day is thrown off.

3. Communicate! If you are running behind or have to cancel reach out in reasonable time apologize for the delay and offer a small discount or something in exchange for the inconvenience. 

4. Change the tone on your booking site. Many potential clients are scared away because the verbiage used on your booking site is intimidating. Making a few small changes to not come across so aggressive will make a world of difference. 

5. Customer Experience! When meeting a new client for the first time how you make them feel is so important. Greet them with a smile when they come in and make them feel welcomed and comfortable. Offer a complimentary snack or beverage during their appointment. The small gestures are always appreciated.

When it comes to attracting customers as a new stylist it’s important to utilize social media. It’s a free app to showcase your work that can potentially reach thousands of people. One post can change your life. Don’t have customers? Model yourself! You are a walking billboard for your brand and every where you go is an opportunity to gain a new client. Keep business cards handy with a QR code to your social media/website for quick and easy access to your portfolio of work. 

Creating content can be a challenge for some. Don’t overthink it! Remember everything is content. Short tutorials and BTS footage usually performs well. Pull out your phone and tripod and capture every thing.  Post 10-15 second reels (people have short attention spans so keep it short and straight to the point).

Consistency and engaging content is how you build a following. Posting 2-3 times a day is the best way to stay in the algorithm. This can be exhausting so when you’re first starting out post at least once a day. You can always recycle old content and repurpose it. Throw old footage over new trending audio with minor tweaks and post it again. IG only shows your content to about 10 percent of your followers, so chances are many of them didn’t see it the first time.

If you don’t know what to post create a theme for each day of the week to keep it consistent. For example:
Sunday Funday
Motivational Monday
Hot Topic Tuesday
Wig of the Week Wednesday
By creating themes for each day you can plan your content and it gives your audience something to look forward to. We’re in a “TikTok taught me” era so educational content is a must. If you can teach and add value people will typically hit that follow button. 

Monitor your posts to see what gets the most engagement and produce content around what performs well on your page.

Unpopular FACT, curly hair is the most difficult texture to maintain. Many ladies opt for curly with the idea that it will be lower maintenance when in fact it requires a lot of TLC to stay presentable. 

If you’re wearing it daily a good shampoo and condition once (maybe even twice) a week to remove product buildup and maintain softness and flow. My go to shampoo and conditioner is silicon mix. Wet and detangle hair in sections daily (never comb curly hair dry)‼️ 

I typically use coconut pudding curl from my girl @slayedbyda_llc on freshly washed hair. For daily maintenance I mix 90% water with 5% leave in conditioner and 5% nairobi (or some form of foaming lotion or curl mousse) to apply daily. Water is the best option for curls. Overuse of products weighs the hair down and causes buildup making it stiff. After the first initial application water reactivates the products anyway, don’t over-apply. 

Hope this helps. ❤️

I have three phases of production for custom wigs.

1. Prepping- during this phase I bleach the knots, color the hair and prepare the wig caps (resize and do the guidelines).
I label the caps with the customers name so I know which cap belongs to who.
2. Construction- I construct all wigs this usually takes a couple days. I typically construct 10-12 wigs a day during this process. I’ll bump it up to 15 if there’s an influx of orders.
3. Styling- during this last phase I customize the wigs (pluck, baby hair if requested and style). 

I batch prep everything at the same time to stay organized. This method has worked efficiently for me for a couple years now. I can’t see doing it any other way without losing my sanity. 

Then as many of you know I only accept custom orders the first week of each month. This has also helped me with time management and trained my clients to place wig orders on a certain timeline. Now I knock out custom orders earlier in the month and spend the last couple weeks working on ready to ship wigs for wig restocks. 

It’s important to come up with a system that works well for you and your business. Especially if you work alone as I do. You have to have a schedule and time management to prevent feeling overwhelmed and burnt out.
